lass="t-p-color icon icon-chevron"></span></li></ul><header class="article__header"><div class="article__strapline"></div><section class="article__headline-section"><span class="article__kicker t-p-color">NIGHT LIGHTS </span><h1 class="article__headline">Perseid meteor shower tonight: What time and how to see the huge bright FIREBALLS over UK again</h1></section></header><div class="article__meta"><div class="article__name-date"><div class="article__author"><ul class="t-p-color article__noLabel article__ul" itemProp="author"><li class="article__author-list t-p-background-color__before"><span class="article__author-name t-p-color">Charlotte Edwards</span><span class="article__author-role t-p-color">, Digital Technology and Science Reporter</span></li></ul></div><ul class="article__time"><li class="article__published"><span class="article__datestamp">16:00, </span><span class="article__timestamp">4 Aug 2020</span></li><li class="article__updated"><span class="article__datestamp"><span class="article__updated-medium">Updated</span>: 21:43, </span><span class="article__timestamp">12 Aug 2020</span></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class="article-switcheroo"><div class="article__content"><p><strong><strong>THE Perseid meteor shower is set to peak this evening, meaning you could see dozens of bright fireballs every hour.</strong></strong></p>
<p>The celestial event happens every August when Earth crosses paths with debris left behind from Comet Swift-Tuttle.</p>
<figure class="article__media"><div class="article__media-img-container open-gallery" data-index="64601"><a href="#"><img alt="You may be able to see 100 meteors an hour" height="635" width="960" class="lazyload" data-src="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg" data-credit="EPA" data-sizes="(max-width: 375px) 335px, (max-width: 520px) 480px, 620px" data-img="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?strip=all&amp;w=960" data-srcSet="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=335 335w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=480 480w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=620 620w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=670 670w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=960 960w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1240 1240w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1005 1005w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1440 1440w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1860 1860w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1340 1340w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=1920 1920w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000426362403.jpg?w=2480 2480w" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 1.5 1&quot;%3E%3C/svg%3E"/></a><div class="article__gallery-count"><span class="article__gallery-count-value">3</span></div></div><figcaption class="article__media-caption"><span class="article__media-span">You may be able to see 100 meteors an hour</span><span class="article__credit">Credit: EPA</span></figcaption></figure>
<div class="advert-wrapper advert-wrapper--in-article-fluid"><div id="in-article-fluid" class="dfp-ad advert--inarticle-fluid"></div></div><p>In 2020, the peak is happening around August 11, 12 and 13.</p>
<p>The meteors appear to radiate from the tip of the Perseus constellation, hence their name.</p>
<p>To see them at their brightest though, look in the late evening tonight and into the early hours of the morning on August 13.</p>
<p>The best time to watch will be from midnight to 5:30am.</p><div class="advert-wrapper advert-wrapper--outstream"><div id="outstream" class="dfp-ad advert--outstream"></div></div>
<figure class="article__media"><div class="article__media-img-container open-gallery" data-index="64602"><a href="#"><img height="768" width="960" class="lazyload" data-src="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg" data-credit="" data-sizes="(max-width: 375px) 335px, (max-width: 520px) 480px, 620px" data-img="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?strip=all&amp;w=960" data-srcSet="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=335 335w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=480 480w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=620 620w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=670 670w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=960 960w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1240 1240w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1005 1005w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1440 1440w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1860 1860w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1340 1340w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=1920 1920w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/pmPerseid-Meteor-Shower-1.jpg?w=2480 2480w" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 1.3 1&quot;%3E%3C/svg%3E"/></a><div class="article__gallery-count"><span class="article__gallery-count-value">3</span></div></div></figure>
<figure class="article__media"><div class="article__media-img-container open-gallery" data-index="64603"><a href="#"><img alt="You&#x27;ll need to look to the sky in the late evening and early hours of the morning to see the meteor shower" height="641" width="960" class="lazyload" data-src="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg" data-credit="AP:Associated Press" data-sizes="(max-width: 375px) 335px, (max-width: 520px) 480px, 620px" data-img="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?strip=all&amp;w=960" data-srcSet="https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=335 335w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=480 480w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=620 620w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=670 670w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=960 960w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1240 1240w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1005 1005w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1440 1440w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1860 1860w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1340 1340w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=1920 1920w, https://www.thesun.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/NINTCHDBPICT000513167351.jpg?w=2480 2480w" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 1.5 1&quot;%3E%3C/svg%3E"/></a><div class="article__gallery-count"><span class="article__gallery-count-value">3</span></div></div><figcaption class="article__media-caption"><span class="article__media-span">You&#x27;ll need to look to the sky in the late evening and early hours of the morning to see the meteor shower</span><span class="article__credit">Credit: AP:Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>You&#x27;ll need to hope for clear skies and look a few hours before sunrise if you want to make out the faintest of meteors.</p>
<p>The Moon shouldn&#x27;t be too bright at this time of the month so that will work in the favour of stargazers.</p>
<p>Typically, the shower displays around 60 meteors an hour but you could see up to 100.</p>
<p>You&#x27;ll need to be in a dark area like the bottom of a garden and try to avoid light pollution.</p><div class="advert-wrapper advert-wrapper--articlempu"><div id="articlempu" class="dfp-ad advert--inarticle"></div></div>
<p>Anna Ross, a Royal Observatory Greenwich astronomer, told the PA: “During the peak night of the shower, you will be able to find it in the north-east of the sky, getting higher throughout the night.&quot;</p>
<p>There are many phone apps that can help you locate constellations in the sky.</p>
<p>Once you&#x27;ve used your phone you&#x27;ll need to give your eyes some time to adjust to the dark again.</p>
<p>A typical Perseid meteor is said to travel at 133,200 mph.</p><div class="advert-wrapper advert-wrapper--advert-inarticle-mpu"><div id="advert-inarticle-mpu" class="dfp-ad advert--in-article-mpu nuk-ad-placeholder" data-ad-label="inArticleMPU"></div></div>
<p>They burn up in our atmosphere and almost none of them hit the ground.</p>
<p>If they do they&#x27;ll then be called a meteorite.</p>
<div class="article-boxout"><div class="article-boxout__header t-p-background-color"><h3 class="article-boxout__headline">What's the difference between an asteroid, meteor and comet?</h3></div><div class="article-boxout__content theme__background-color-rgba-20"><p class="article__content--intro">Here's what you need to know, according to Nasa...</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Asteroid:</strong> An asteroid is a small rocky body that orbits the Sun. Most are found in the asteroid belt (between Mars and Jupiter) but they can be found anywhere (including in a path that can impact Earth)</li>
<li><strong>Meteoroid:</strong> When two asteroids hit each other, the small chunks that break off are called meteoroids</li>
<li><strong>Meteor:</strong> If a meteoroid enters the Earth&#x27;s atmosphere, it begins to vapourise and then becomes a meteor. On Earth, it&#x27;ll look like a streak of light in the sky, because the rock is burning up</li>
<li><strong>Meteorite:</strong> If a meteoroid doesn&#x27;t vapourise completely and survives the trip through Earth&#x27;s atmosphere, it can land on the Earth. At that point, it becomes a meteorite</li>
<li><strong>Comet:</strong> Like asteroids, a comet orbits the Sun. However rather than being made mostly of rock, a comet contains lots of ice and gas, which can result in amazing tails forming behind them (thanks to the ice and dust vapourising)</li>
</ul>
